AB  - The Piedmont South was historically characterized by strong linkages between its rural industries and urban distribution centers. These linkages have been diminished since the decline of the region’s textile and furniture industries in the early 1990s. After witnessing the growing inequality produced by this loss of economic and social interactions between the urban and rural portions of the Charlotte area, the UNC Charlotte Urban Institute embarked on the Carolinas Urban-Rural Connection (CURC) project in 2017. The intent of the project was to engage rural and small-town residents in the 75 miles around Charlotte and identify how the urban and rural economies of the region might be reconnected. Using the theoretical context of new regionalism, we encountered two trends we considered to be significant explanatory factors in rural economic decline and eventual resurgence. The first was an issue of leadership: small towns are struggling to identify and retain a new cohort of community leaders. The second was an issue of community identity: small towns are often challenged to cultivate unique economic, cultural, or social identities. However, we found them to be necessary to support meaningful economic development. This note outlines these two issues as they relate to rural and urban connections and interdependence. © 2021, University of North Carolina Press. All rights reserved.
