AB  - Russia declared itself the protector of Russian-speakers living in former Soviet Republics in the early 1990s and utilized a variety of hard and soft power mechanisms to influence ethnopolitics in those states. After the Baltic States gained membership in both NATO and the EU in 2004, Russia began to place more emphasis on “softer” mechanisms of influence and to rely less on military and economic levers. These “softer” mechanisms include cultivating ties with Russian-speakers through compatriot organizations, supporting cultural and educational initiatives, and using the Russian media to influence public opinion. Through an analysis of recent parliamentary debates over education and naturalization policies, this article demonstrates how Russia’s soft power agenda provides a key context in which Latvia’s policies toward Russian-speakers are made. Policymakers use Russian “soft power” frames to shape policies in more exclusionary and inclusionary directions. Consequently, while Russia may possess significant soft power resources, its influence on policymaking in target states depends to a large extent on how policymakers frame Russia’s agenda within domestic policy debates. © 2020 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group.
