AB  - Although older adults are often seen as warm, they also may be viewed as incompetent. These perceptions of incompetence have implications for the context of immigration, whereby older immigrants may be viewed as a burden on the economy and public services and unlikely to integrate into society. The current research examined whether attitudes toward immigrant targets differ as a function of the target’s age. Studies 1 (N = 85) and 2 (N = 202) tested this question with Canadian samples and found that older immigrant targets were viewed more negatively than young adult immigrant targets, and that this was explained by the belief that older adult immigrants will have a negative impact on the economy and be a burden on public services (i.e., realistic threat). Moreover, older adult nonimmigrants were also viewed more negatively than young adult nonimmigrants, suggesting this effect may be driven by ageism. These findings demonstrate the complexity of attitudes toward immigrants and suggest that a variety of identities must be considered when studying evaluations of immigrant targets. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved) Public Significance Statement: Immigration attitudes are complex, likely because of the multiple identities immigrants may hold. These studies found that one identity that is important for determining attitudes toward immigrants is age. Indeed, it was found that older adult immigrants were viewed more negatively than young adult immigrants because they were seen as less likely to contribute to the economy and more likely to be a burden on public services. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved) Bien que les personnes âgées puissent souvent être perçues comme étant chaleureuses, elles peuvent aussi être vues comme étant incompétentes. La perception d’incompétence a des répercussions dans le contexte de l’immigration, car les immigrants âgés peuvent être perçus comme un fardeau pour l’économie et les services publics et jugés peu susceptibles de s’intégrer dans la société. La présente recherche examine si les attitudes à l’égard des objectifs d’immigration varient selon le groupe d’âge cible. Les Études (N = 85) et 2 (N = 202) ont examiné cette question au sein d’échantillons canadiens. Elles révèlent que les immigrants âgés étaient perçus plus négativement que les jeunes adultes immigrants. Ces résultats s’expliquent par la croyance que les immigrants âgés auront une incidence négative sur l’économie et qu’ils constitueront un fardeau pour les services publics (c.-à-d., une menace réaliste). En outre, les perceptions à l’égard des personnes âgées non immigrantes étaient aussi plus négatives que celles à l’égard des jeunes adultes non immigrants, ce qui pourrait être attribuable à l’âgisme. Ces résultats révèlent la complexité des attitudes à l’égard des immigrants et suggèrent qu’une pluralité d’identités doit être considérée dans les études de l’évaluation des objectifs d’immigration. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved) © 2020 Canadian Psychological Association
